TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Effect of Early-Childhood Education on Social Preferences
AU  - Cappelen, Alexander
AU  - List, John
AU  - Samek, Anya
AU  - Tungodden, Bertil
Y1  - 2019/10/14
PY  - 2019
DA  - 2020/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/706858
DO  - 10.1086/706858
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 2739
EP  - 2758
VL  - 128
IS  - 7
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We present results from the first study to examine the causal impact of early-childhood education on the social preferences of children. We compare children who, at 3?4 years old, were randomized into either a full-time preschool, a parenting program, or a control group. We returned to the children when they reached 6?8 years of age and conducted a series of incentivized experiments to elicit their social preferences. We find that early-childhood education has a strong causal impact on social preferences. Our findings highlight the importance of taking a broad perspective when designing and evaluating early-childhood educational programs.
AB  - We present results from the first study to examine the causal impact of early-childhood education on the social preferences of children. We compare children who, at 3?4 years old, were randomized into either a full-time preschool, a parenting program, or a control group. We returned to the children when they reached 6?8 years of age and conducted a series of incentivized experiments to elicit their social preferences. We find that early-childhood education has a strong causal impact on social preferences. Our findings highlight the importance of taking a broad perspective when designing and evaluating early-childhood educational programs.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/706858
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/706858
Y2  - 2024/03/20
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Revealed-Preference Analysis with Framing Effects
AU  - Goldin, Jacob
AU  - Reck, Daniel
Y1  - 2019/10/14
PY  - 2019
DA  - 2020/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/706860
DO  - 10.1086/706860
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 2759
EP  - 2795
VL  - 128
IS  - 7
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - In many settings, decision makers? behavior is observed to vary on the basis of seemingly arbitrary factors. Such framing effects cast doubt on the welfare conclusions drawn from revealed-preference analysis. We relax the assumptions underlying that approach to accommodate settings in which framing effects are present. Plausible restrictions of varying strength permit either partial or point identification of preferences for the decision makers who choose consistently across frames. Recovering population preferences requires understanding the empirical relationship between decision makers? preferences and their sensitivity to the frame. We develop tools for studying this relationship and illustrate them with data on automatic enrollment into pension plans.
AB  - In many settings, decision makers? behavior is observed to vary on the basis of seemingly arbitrary factors. Such framing effects cast doubt on the welfare conclusions drawn from revealed-preference analysis. We relax the assumptions underlying that approach to accommodate settings in which framing effects are present. Plausible restrictions of varying strength permit either partial or point identification of preferences for the decision makers who choose consistently across frames. Recovering population preferences requires understanding the empirical relationship between decision makers? preferences and their sensitivity to the frame. We develop tools for studying this relationship and illustrate them with data on automatic enrollment into pension plans.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/706860
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/706860
Y2  - 2024/03/20
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - A Random Attention Model
AU  - Cattaneo, Matias D.
AU  - Ma, Xinwei
AU  - Masatlioglu, Yusufcan
AU  - Suleymanov, Elchin
Y1  - 2019/10/14
PY  - 2019
DA  - 2020/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/706861
DO  - 10.1086/706861
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 2796
EP  - 2836
VL  - 128
IS  - 7
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This paper illustrates how one can deduce preference from observed choices when attention is both limited and random. We introduce a random attention model where we abstain from any particular attention formation and instead consider a large class of nonparametric random attention rules. Our intuitive condition, monotonic attention, captures the idea that each consideration set competes for the decision maker?s attention. We then develop a revealed preference theory and obtain testable implications. We propose econometric methods for identification, estimation, and inference for the revealed preferences. Finally, we provide a general-purpose software implementation of our estimation and inference results and simulation evidence.
AB  - This paper illustrates how one can deduce preference from observed choices when attention is both limited and random. We introduce a random attention model where we abstain from any particular attention formation and instead consider a large class of nonparametric random attention rules. Our intuitive condition, monotonic attention, captures the idea that each consideration set competes for the decision maker?s attention. We then develop a revealed preference theory and obtain testable implications. We propose econometric methods for identification, estimation, and inference for the revealed preferences. Finally, we provide a general-purpose software implementation of our estimation and inference results and simulation evidence.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/706861
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/706861
Y2  - 2024/03/20
